What is Spring Framework?

Spring Framework is a powerful, open-source framework for building Java applications,
especially enterprise-level apps. Spring manages the "plumbing" (infrastructure code)
(boilerplate code) so you can focus on business logic.

Advantages of Spring Framework:

a. Loose Coupling
What it means: Components (classes, services, etc.) in your application are independent of
each other.
Why it matters: If you change one part, others are not affected. This makes your code easier
to maintain and test.
How Spring achieves this: Through Dependency Injection (DI) and Inversion of Control (IoC).

b. Inversion of Control (IoC) and Dependency Injection (DI)
IoC: Instead of your code creating objects, the Spring container does it for you. The control
of object creation is "inverted" from your code to the framework.
DI: Spring injects dependencies (objects your class needs) automatically, either via
constructor, setter, or field injection.

Example:

@Component
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;

    // Constructor Injection
    @Autowired
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }
}
Here, UserRepository is injected into UserService by Spring, not manually created.

c. Modular Architecture
What it means: Spring is divided into modules (Core, AOP, Data Access, Web, etc.). You only
use what you need.
Why it matters: Your application stays lightweight and efficient.

d. Scalability
What it means: Spring can handle small to very large applications.
Why it matters: As your project grows, Spring can support more features and higher loads
without major rewrites.

